Modify the following plot to change the color of all points to "pink".

ggplot(starwars, 
       aes(x = height, y = mass, color = gender, size = birth_year)) +
  geom_point(color = "pink")

Add labels for title, x and y axes, and size of points.

library(viridis)
ggplot(starwars, 
       aes(x = height, y = mass, color = gender, size = birth_year)) +
  geom_point(color = "#30509C") +
  labs(
    title = "Mass by Height x Gender x Birth Year",
    x = "Height", 
    y = "Mass",
    size = "Birth Year"
    )

Pick a single categorical variable from the data set and make a bar plot of its distribution.

ggplot(starwars, aes(homeworld, fill = homeworld)) +
  geom_bar() +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "mako") +
  guides(fill = "none") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip()

Pick a single numerical variable and make a histogram of it.

(This time no starter code is provided, youâre on your own!)

ggplot(starwars, aes(mass)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "blue", fill = "purple") +
  theme_minimal()

Pick a numerical variable and a categorical variable and make a visualisation (you pick the type!) to visualise the relationship between the two variables. Along with your code and output, provide an interpretation of the visualisation.

ggplot(starwars %>% filter(!is.na(gender)), aes(x = gender, y = mass, fill = gender)) +
  stat_summary(geom = "bar", fun = "mean") +
  guides(fill = "none") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "mako") +
  theme_minimal()
